{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658264"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20720"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96904"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13596"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79519"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"11655"},{"type":"tags","id":"12599"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96904"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe successful transmission of infectious agents between hosts depends on multiple factors including the pathogen\u0027s exit strategy, environmental stability, and entry mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between a pathogen\u0027s transmission route and its biological characteristics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contact-dependent pathogens have high environmental stability","Direct contact pathogens have low environmental stability","Respiratory pathogens require moist environments only","Enteric pathogens need acidic conditions for survival","Blood-borne pathogens survive best in alkaline media"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect contact pathogens have low environmental stability\u003C/strong\u003E. These microorganisms cannot survive for extended periods outside a host and must be passed quickly from person to person. They have evolved efficient direct transmission mechanisms to compensate for their environmental vulnerability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact-dependent pathogens have high environmental stability\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as contact-dependent pathogens typically have poor survival outside their hosts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory pathogens require moist environments only\u003C/strong\u003E - While moisture is important, other factors like temperature and pH also affect survival\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteric pathogens need acidic conditions for survival\u003C/strong\u003E - Many enteric pathogens actually survive better in neutral or slightly alkaline conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood-borne pathogens survive best in alkaline media\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood-borne pathogens are typically adapted to survive at physiological pH, not specifically alkaline conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the relationship between transmission routes and pathogen characteristics is crucial for infection control. Most human pathogens are transmitted via respiratory, faecal-oral, or sexual routes, with their biological properties closely matched to their primary transmission strategy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pathogens that require direct contact for transmission typically have low environmental stability and cannot survive long outside a host.","Most human pathogens are transmitted via respiratory, faecal-oral, or sexual routes.","A pathogen\u0027s transmission route is closely linked to its biological characteristics and survival capabilities."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 342."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:48:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:51:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13596"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96904"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11654"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"General principles of microbial pathogenesis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18: